s a specific area of mathematics. The MSC is maintained by the American Mathematical Society (AMS) and Zentralblatt MATH as part of the Mathematics Subject Classification Scheme developed by the Mathematics Subject Classification Task Force.\n\nThe MSC 2000 is updated periodically to reflect the changing nature of mathematics. Each class is assigned a unique code consisting of one or more letters and digits. For example, the class for Algebra is 12, and the class for Algebraic Geometry is 14A.\n\nThe editors for the MSC 2000 are the editors of the Mathematics Subject Classification Scheme. The MSC 2000 was developed by the Mathematics Subject Classification 2000 Task Force, chaired by Robin J. Wilson, a Kendall Professor of Mathematics at the London School of Economics.\n\nThe MSC 2000 is widely used in the indexing and abstracting of mathematical literature, and it helps researchers and librarians to organize and locate mathematical resources efficiently. The classes in the MSC are organized in a hierarchical manner, with broader classes at the top and more specific classes below. They are organized according to the Mathematics Subject Classification 1991 classes, which were served by the MSC 1991 Task Force. However, the MSC 2000 was developed independently by a group of mathematicians and is considered more modern and accurate than the previous classification system.\n\nThe final answer is:\n\\boxed{\\text{The 2000 Mathematics Subject Classification (MSC) is a hierarchical classification system maintained by the American Mathematical Society (AMS) and Zentralblatt MATH.}}\n\nThe graph of \\(x^{2}+y^{2}=9\\) is a circle with radius 3 cm. If the rate at which the radius is increasing with respect to time \\(t\\) is 2 cm/s, at what rate, in square cm/s, is the area of the circle increasing?\nTo solve this problem, we need to find the rate at which the area of the circle is increasing with respect to time \\(t\\). The area \\(A\\) of a circle is given by the formula: